'''NuScale Power Corporation''' is a publicly traded American company that designs and markets [[small modular reactor]]s (SMRs). It is headquartered in [[Tigard, Oregon]]. The company's VOYGR power plant, which uses 50 MWe modules and scales to 12 modules (600 MWe), was the first SMR to be certified by the US [[Nuclear Regulatory Commission]] (NRC) (2022).<ref>{{cite web |title=NRC Certifies First U.S. Small Modular Reactor Design |url=https://www.energy.gov/ne/articles/nrc-certifies-first-us-small-modular-reactor-design |access-date=June 12, 2025 |website=energy.gov/ |publisher=DOE}}</ref> The newer 77 MWe module designs, known as the VOYGR-4 (308 MWe) and VOYGR-6 (462 MWe), were submitted for NRC review on January 1, 2023, and approved May 29, 2025.<ref name="nrc-20221231" /> NuScale is now seeking NRC approval for their 12-module, VOYGR-12. The SMR is also scalable, offering up to 924 MWe.<ref name=":4">{{cite web |title=NuScale SMR plants become VOYGR |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/NuScale-SMR-plants-become-VOYGR |access-date=May 31, 2025 |website=world-nuclear-news.org |publisher=World Nuclear Association}}</ref> 

NuScale Power Modules are surrounded by a {{convert|9|ft|m}} diameter by {{convert|65|ft|m}} tall [[reactor vessel]] that relies on conventional cooling methods. The modules run on [[low enriched uranium]] fuel assemblies based on existing [[light water reactor]] designs. For a 12-module configuration, the modules are stored individually in submerged storage wells on the floor of a shared 75-foot deep, 10-million-gallon [[Thermal reservoir|reservoir]], and covered by a concrete barrier.<ref>{{cite web |title=NuScale Plant Design Overview |url=https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML1221/ML12216A392.pdf |access-date=June 12, 2025 |website=nrc.gov |publisher=NRC}}</ref> A [[natural convection]] coolant loop is relied upon to feed all of the modules used in a plant. The patented system is capable of delivering additional fresh water to each [[reactor vessel]] without powered pumps in the event of an emergency.<ref name="oregon">{{Citation |last=Parks |first=Bradley W. |title=An Oregon company is going public to raise money for nuclear power ambitions |date=December 14, 2021 |work=[[Oregon Public Broadcasting]] |url=https://www.opb.org/article/2021/12/14/oregon-company-nuscale-power-going-public-nuclear-power-plans/ |access-date=May 7, 2023}}</ref>

NuScale had an agreement to build reactors in Idaho by 2030, but it was canceled in 2023 due to the estimated cost having increased from $3.6 billion to $9.3 billion for the original VOYGR power plant.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Ridler |first=Keith |date=September 2, 2020 |title=US gives first-ever OK for small commercial nuclear reactor |url=https://apnews.com/article/technology-or-state-wire-ut-state-wire-id-state-wire-science-910766c07afd96fbe2bd875e16087464 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210802182425/https://apnews.com/article/technology-or-state-wire-ut-state-wire-id-state-wire-science-910766c07afd96fbe2bd875e16087464 |archive-date=August 2, 2021 |publisher=[[Associated Press]]}}</ref><ref name="eenews-20231109">{{cite news |last=Bright |first=Zach |date=November 9, 2023 |title=NuScale cancels first-of-a-kind nuclear project as costs surge |url=https://www.eenews.net/articles/nuscale-cancels-first-of-a-kind-nuclear-project-as-costs-surge/ |access-date=November 9, 2023 |website=E&E News |publisher=POLITICO}}</ref> As of 2025, the company has a number of contracts under negotiation around the world, including Romania<ref>{{cite web |title=Romania's NuScale SMR plan gets USD275 million boost |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/NuScale-s-Romanian-SMR-plan-gets-USD275-million-bo |access-date=July 18, 2025 |website=world-nuclear-news.org |publisher=World Nuclear News}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Future nuclear power plant with SMR from Doicești: NuScale obtained design approval in the US for the 77 MW module to be installed in Romania |url=https://energyworld.ro/2025/05/30/future-nuclear-power-plant-with-smr-from-doicesti-nuscale-obtained-design-approval-in-the-us-for-the-77-mw-module-to-be-installed-in-romania/ |access-date=July 24, 2025 |website=energyworld.ro |publisher=Energy World}}</ref> and Tennessee.<ref name="nei-20250905">{{cite news |date=September 5, 2025 |title=TVA, ENTRA1 plan SMR deployment |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/tva-entra1-plan-smr-deployment/ |access-date=September 6, 2025 |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International}}</ref> More SMR interest has come from tech giants who are looking to power US-based data centers. NuScale's design is the only approved design for use in the US.

==History==
NuScale was founded based on research conducted by a team of nuclear scientists at [[Oregon State University]] (OSU) and the [[Idaho National Laboratory]] (INL) and funded by the [[United States Department of Energy]] (DOE) beginning in 2000.<ref name="three" /><ref name="one">{{cite news |last=Hyatt |first=Abraham |date=July 2008 |title=Start Me Up: NuScale Power |url=http://www.oregonbusiness.com/archives/24-july-2008/364-start-me-up |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120830024753/http://www.oregonbusiness.com/archives/24-july-2008/364-start-me-up |archive-date=August 30, 2012 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=Oregon Business}}</ref><ref name="two">{{cite news |date=November 11, 2008 |title=NIMBY: Nukes in my Backyard |url=http://news.investors.com/111008-449804-nimby-nukes-in-my-backyard.htm?p=2 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=Investors Business Daily}}</ref> OSU researchers, headed by José N. Reyes Jr. developed a prototype SMR in 2007, which NuScale Power used to develop its prototype.<ref>{{cite web |title=José N. Reyes Jr. Biography |url=https://www.nae.edu/19579/19711/317876/326607/331293/331454/Jos-N-Reyes-Jr |access-date=May 31, 2025 |website=nae.edu |publisher=National Academy of Engineering}}</ref><ref name="profile">{{cite news |last=Wagman |first=David |date=October 1, 2013 |title=NuScale Puts Single-Minded Focus on Small Modular Reactor |url=http://www.powermag.com/nuscale-puts-single-minded-focus-on-small-modular-reactor/?pagenum=2 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150924080735/http://www.powermag.com/nuscale-puts-single-minded-focus-on-small-modular-reactor/?pagenum=2 |archive-date=September 24, 2015 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=Power Magazine}}</ref> Much of the research was performed at OSU's Multi-Application Small Light Water Reactor (MASLWR) test facility starting in 2007, with full-scale prototype testing performed in Idaho at the INL in 2013.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Mascari |first1=Fulvio |title=International Agreement Report – Analysis of the OSU-MASLWR 001 and 002 Tests by Using the TRACE Code (NUREG/IA-0466) |url=https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/nuregs/agreement/ia0466/index.html |access-date=May 31, 2025 |website=nrc.gov |publisher=Nuclear Regulatory Commission}}</ref> DOE funded the research from 2000 to 2003.

The same year Oregon State University constructed its one-third-scale reactor test facility (MASLWR), the university founded NuScale Power. Joint research between OSU and NuScale soon followed. As compensation for past research, OSU offered researchers opportunities to exchange patents for an equity stake in the new company.<ref name="profile" /><ref>{{cite news |date=April 6, 2009 |title=Small-Scale Nuclear Co. Hunts For Funds |url=http://business.highbeam.com/435572/article-1G1-199099402/smallscale-nuclear-co-hunts-funds |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160310003029/https://business.highbeam.com/435572/article-1G1-199099402/smallscale-nuclear-co-hunts-funds |archive-date=March 10, 2016 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=Power Finance & Risk}}</ref><ref name="eighteen" /> NuScale's first [[Venture round|round in funding]] came in January 2008. The next month it began seeking certification with the NRC.<ref name="two" /><ref name="profile" />

By 2011, NuScale had raised $35 million and had 100 employees in Tigard; Richland, Washington; and Corvallis, Oregon.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogoway |first=Mike |date=January 20, 2011 |title=Corvallis-Based NuScale Suspends Operations after SEC Acts Against its Chief Investor |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2011/01/corvallis-based_nuscale_suspen.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304070832/http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2011/01/corvallis-based_nuscale_suspen.html |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> NuScale was the first to submit small reactor plans to the NRC<ref name="two" /> and the first to gain approval.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web |date=August 28, 2020 |title=NRC Issues Final Safety Evaluation Report for NuScale Small Modular Reactor |url=https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2020/20-043.pdf |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200915214141/https://www.nrc.gov/reading-rm/doc-collections/news/2020/20-043.pdf |archive-date=September 15, 2020 |access-date=September 15, 2020 |website=United States Nuclear Regulatory Commission}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |last=Levitan |first=Dave |date=September 9, 2020 |title=First U.S. Small Nuclear Reactor Design Is Approved |url=https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/first-u-s-small-nuclear-reactor-design-is-approved |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200915214456/https://www.scientificamerican.com/article/first-u-s-small-nuclear-reactor-design-is-approved/ |archive-date=September 15, 2020 |access-date=September 15, 2020 |work=Scientific American}}</ref> It was evaluated by a consortium of utility companies called [[Energy Northwest]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Barbe |first=Wayne |date=June 9, 2009 |title=Energy Northwest Considers Adding Capacity with Modular Nukes |newspaper=Generation Markets Week}}</ref>

===Funding difficulties and rebound===
In January 2011, NuScale's largest investor, Kenwood Group, was investigated by the [[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) and later pleaded guilty to operating a [[Ponzi scheme]]. The SEC investigation was not related to Kenwood's dealings with NuScale, but Kenwood's assets were frozen just as NuScale was expecting additional funding. The company started making staffing and pay cuts as executives looked for new funding sources<ref>{{cite news |date=February 7, 2011 |title=NuScale Cuts Back As Feds Sue Funder |url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/59407581/nuscale-cuts-back-as-feds-sue-funder |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304023616/http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/59407581/nuscale-cuts-back-as-feds-sue-funder |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=The Energy Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Rogoway |first=Mike |date=January 31, 2011 |title=NuScale Furloughs 30, Cuts Pay and Hours for the Others, While it Seeks New Investment |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2011/01/nuscale_furloughs_30_cuts_pay.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115224/http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2011/01/nuscale_furloughs_30_cuts_pay.html |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> and most of the company's employees were laid off.<ref>{{cite news |last=Patel |first=Sonal |date=July 1, 2011 |title=Holtec, Westinghouse Roll Out Small Modular Reactor Designs |url=http://www.powermag.com/holtec-westinghouse-roll-out-small-modular-reactor-designs/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718081530/http://www.powermag.com/holtec-westinghouse-roll-out-small-modular-reactor-designs/ |archive-date=July 18, 2014 |access-date=January 18, 2015 |newspaper=Power Magazine}}</ref>

That September, NuScale obtained a loan to re-hire 60 employees.<ref name="eleven">{{cite news |last=Hall |first=Bennett |date=August 21, 2011 |title=Power Struggle |url=http://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/power-struggle/article_933034dd-b0e8-5c17-bfda-ff1296c95e05.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190514111848/https://www.gazettetimes.com/news/local/power-struggle/article_933034dd-b0e8-5c17-bfda-ff1296c95e05.html |archive-date=May 14, 2019 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=Corvallis Gazette-Times}}</ref> In October, [[Fluor Corporation]] acquired a majority interest in the company for $3.5 million and promised almost $30 million in working capital.<ref name="eighteen">{{cite news |last=Smith |first=Rebecca |date=October 13, 2011 |title=Fluor Buys Stake in Reactor Maker |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204774604576627360588957324 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304220355/http://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052970204774604576627360588957324 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref> According to ''The Energy Daily'', Fluor's investment saved the company, which had been "financially marooned" by its prior investor.<ref name="thirteen">{{cite news |last=Lobsenz |first=George |date=October 14, 2011 |title=Fluor Moves Into Small Reactors With NuScale Buy |url=http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/67547118/fluor-moves-small-reactors-nuscale-buy |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303234703/http://connection.ebscohost.com/c/articles/67547118/fluor-moves-small-reactors-nuscale-buy |archive-date=March 3, 2016 |newspaper=The Energy Daily}}</ref> A separate agreement gave Fluor the rights to construct NuScale-based power plants.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 13, 2011 |title=Fluor Gets Nuclear Firm Stranded By Illarramendi's Ponzi Scheme |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/fluor-nuscale-idUSN1E79C13U20111013 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120223080410/http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/10/13/fluor-nuscale-idUSN1E79C13U20111013 |archive-date=February 23, 2012 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |publisher=Reuters}}</ref>

In August 2012, [[Rolls-Royce Holdings]] said it would support NuScale's commercialization efforts and help it obtain funding from DOE's [[funding opportunity announcement]].<ref name="profile" /> In December 2012, co-founder Paul G. Lorenzini was replaced by John Hopkins as CEO.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogoway |first=Mike |date=December 13, 2012 |title=NuScale Power Replaces CEO |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2012/12/nuscale_power_replaces_ceo.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304071010/http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2012/12/nuscale_power_replaces_ceo.html |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=January 29, 2015 |newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> It was not funded in the first DOE's round.<ref>{{cite news |last=Rogoway |first=Mike |date=March 27, 2013 |title=NuScale Power Begins Fresh Effort to Secure Federal Funds for its Nuclear Technology |url=http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2013/03/nuscale_power_begins_fresh_eff.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903192826/http://www.oregonlive.com/business/index.ssf/2013/03/nuscale_power_begins_fresh_eff.html |archive-date=September 3, 2014 |access-date=January 29, 2015 |newspaper=The Oregonian}}</ref> In the second round in December 2013, NuScale won up to $226 million in "cost-sharing" funding to share the expense of obtaining government approval, through the SMR Licensing Technical Support program.<ref name="seventeen">{{cite news |date=April 2014 |title=NuScale joins B&W on the SMR bench |url=http://www.modernpowersystems.com/features/featurenuscale-joins-bw-on-the-smr-bench-4264827/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140602012154/http://www.modernpowersystems.com/features/featurenuscale-joins-bw-on-the-smr-bench-4264827/ |archive-date=June 2, 2014 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=Modern Power Systems}}</ref> This was followed by an agreement in May 2014 for up to $217 million in funding over a five-year period, whereby DOE would match private funding.<ref name="fifteen">{{cite news |last=Patel |first=Sonal |date=May 29, 2014 |title=NuScale, DOE Complete Agreement for $217M SMR Development Funds |url=http://www.powermag.com/nuscale-doe-complete-agreement-for-271m-smr-development-funds/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716044655/http://www.powermag.com/nuscale-doe-complete-agreement-for-271m-smr-development-funds/ |archive-date=July 16, 2014 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=Power Magazine}}</ref><ref name="reuters-20131213">{{cite news |last=Reddall |first=Braden |date=December 13, 2013 |title=Fluor's NuScale lands U.S. govt funding for new small reactors |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/fluor-nuscale-funding-idUSL1N0JR2HF20131213 |url-access=limited |access-date=November 11, 2023 |publisher=Reuters}}</ref>

In September 2020, the U.S. [[Department of Energy]] reported that it had provided more than $400 million since 2014 to support the NuScale development and that of other earlier stage domestic SMR designs.<ref name=doe-20200902 />

=== 2022 launch as a public company ===
In December 2021, the [[Fluor Corporation]] reported that it had invested over $600 million in NuScale since 2011, and that NuScale was expected to go public in 2022 with Fluor owning about 60% of the stock.<ref name="govconwire-20211215">{{cite news |last=Edwards |first=Jane |date=December 15, 2021 |title=Fluor-Backed NuScale Power to Go Public Through Spring Valley Merger; Alan Boeckmann Quoted |url=https://www.govconwire.com/2021/12/fluor-backed-nuscale-power-to-go-public-through-spring-valley-merger/ |access-date=November 11, 2023 |website=GovConWire}}</ref> In May 2022, NuScale completed a merger with the [[special-purpose acquisition company]] (SPAC), Spring Valley Acquisition Corp, raising $380 million of investment. NuScale Power Corporation then listed on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref name=":3">{{cite journal |date=May 3, 2022 |title=Nuclear-Tech Firm NuScale Gains After Completing SPAC Merger |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2022-05-03/nuclear-company-nuscale-gains-day-after-completing-spac-merger |journal=Bloomberg |access-date=May 6, 2022}}</ref>

In September 2022, NuScale entered into an alliance with ENTRA1 Energy and the private asset management firm [[Habboush Group]] to commercialize the NuScale SMR.<ref name="nuscalepower-20220909">{{cite web |date=September 9, 2022 |title=NuScale Power, Habboush Group and ENTRA1 form Strategic Alliance |url=https://www.nuscalepower.com/press-releases/2022/nuscale-power-habboush-group-and-entra1-form-strategic-alliance |access-date=August 25, 2025 |website=NuScale Power}}</ref> In May 2025, the relationship was described as "ENTRA1 Energy is NuScale's partner and independent power plant development platform, which holds the global exclusive rights to the commercialisation, distribution, and deployment of NuScale's SMRs." NuScale Power now limits itself to the production of the SMR modules rather than entire power plants.<ref name="wnn-20250530">{{cite news |date=May 30, 2025 |title=Uprated NuScale SMR design gets US approval |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/articles/uprated-nuscale-smr-design-gets-us-approval |access-date=August 16, 2025 |website=World Nuclear News}}</ref><ref name="nuscale-entra1">{{cite web |title=ENTRA1 and Nuscale Partnership |url=https://interactive.nuscalepower.com/nuscale/nuscale-entra1-partnership/p/1 |access-date=August 25, 2025 |website=NuScale Power}}</ref> ENTRA1 and NuScale own a joint venture company, ENTRA1 NuScale LLC.<ref name=nei-20250905 />

=== Carbon Free Power Project, Idaho ===
In November 2014, NuScale announced it would build what it expected to be the first US SMR at the [[Idaho National Laboratory]].<ref name="inl-20200602">{{cite web |date=June 2, 2020 |title=What is the Carbon Free Power Project? |url=https://inl.gov/nuclear-energy/frequently-asked-questions/ |access-date=November 27, 2023 |website=Idaho National Laboratory}}</ref> The plant was for Utah Associated Municipal Power Systems (UAMPS), a subdivision of the [[Government of Utah]], on the Carbon Free Power Project (CFPP).<ref name="cfpp-website">{{cite web |title=CFPP LLC |url=https://www.cfppllc.com/ |access-date=November 9, 2023 |website=Carbon Free Power Project}}</ref> UAMPS operates power plants in Wyoming, New Mexico, California, and Utah, selling to local utilities. The DOE could provide supporting funds of about $140 million/year over 10 years, awaiting more Congressional support.<ref name=":5">{{Cite web |date=July 21, 2021 |title=UAMPS downsizes NuScale SMR plans |url=https://www.ans.org/news/article-3087/uamps-downsizes-nuscale-smr-plans/ |access-date=December 4, 2022 |website=Nuclear Newswire |language=en-us}}</ref>

The company submitted designs to the NRC in January 2017 for a 12 reactor power plant producing 570 MWe at a build cost under $3 billion.<ref>{{cite web |author=Geoff Brumfiel |date=January 13, 2017 |title=Miniaturized Nuclear Power Plant? U.S. Reviewing Proposed Design |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/13/509673094/miniaturized-nuclear-power-plant-u-s-reviewing-proposed-design |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180726201746/https://www.npr.org/sections/thetwo-way/2017/01/13/509673094/miniaturized-nuclear-power-plant-u-s-reviewing-proposed-design |archive-date=July 26, 2018 |access-date=April 5, 2018 |website=[[NPR]]}}</ref><ref name="doe-20200902">{{cite web |date=September 2, 2020 |title=NRC Approves First U.S. Small Modular Reactor Design |url=https://www.energy.gov/ne/articles/nrc-approves-first-us-small-modular-reactor-design |access-date=November 14, 2023 |publisher=U.S. Department of Energy}}</ref> In 2020, DOE approved a $1.355 billion cost-share award.<ref name="wnn-20201019">{{cite news |date=October 19, 2020 |title=US government backs NuScale projects at home and abroad |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/US-government-backs-NuScale-projects-at-home-and-a |access-date=January 10, 2023 |publisher=World Nuclear News}}</ref>

As of 2021, 8 cities had withdrawn from CFPP.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Patel |first=Sonal |date=October 29, 2020 |title=Shakeup for 720-MW Nuclear SMR Project as More Cities Withdraw Participation |url=https://www.powermag.com/shakeup-for-720-mw-nuclear-smr-project-as-more-cities-withdraw-participation/ |access-date=August 10, 2022 |website=POWER Magazine |language=en-US}}</ref>  In July 2021, the proposal was downsized to 6 reactors, and the expected electricity price increased to $58/MWh (¢5.8/kWh).<ref name=":5" />

In April 2022, [[Doosan Enerbility]] was contracted to begin manufacturing power module components for CFPP. Doosan Enerbility expected to reach full-scale production at their plant in [[Changwon]], South Korea, in the second half of 2023.<ref>{{Cite web |title=Full-scale production of NuScale SMR to begin : New Nuclear – World Nuclear News |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Full-scale-production-of-NuScale-SMR-to-begin |access-date=May 11, 2022 |website=www.world-nuclear-news.org}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |last=Patel |first=Sonal |date=April 26, 2022 |title=Doosan Kicks Off NuScale SMR Production for Idaho Nuclear Project |url=https://www.powermag.com/doosan-kicks-off-nuscale-smr-production-for-idaho-nuclear-project/ |access-date=May 11, 2022 |website=POWER Magazine |language=en-US}}</ref>

In January 2023, CFPP approved a new Budget and Plan of Finance, establishing a target price of $89/MWh (¢8.9/kWh) after an estimated $30/MWh generation subsidy from the 2022 [[Inflation Reduction Act]] (IRA).<ref name="wnn-20230109">{{cite news |date=January 9, 2023 |title=Further cost refinements announced for first US SMR plant |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Further-cost-refinements-announced-for-first-US-SM |access-date=January 10, 2023 |publisher=World Nuclear News}}</ref><ref name="ieefa-20230111">{{cite web |last=Schlissel |first=David |author-link=David A. Schlissel |date=January 11, 2023 |title=Eye-popping new cost estimates released for NuScale small modular reactor |url=https://ieefa.org/resources/eye-popping-new-cost-estimates-released-nuscale-small-modular-reactor |access-date=January 27, 2023 |website=Institute for Energy Economics & Financial Analysis}}</ref> The projected build cost had increased to $9.3 billion for 462 MWe generation capacity from $3.6 billion for 720 MWe in 2020.<ref name="guardian-20231109">{{cite news |last=Morton |first=Adam |date=November 9, 2023 |title=Small modular nuclear reactor that was hailed by Coalition as future cancelled due to rising costs |url=https://www.theguardian.com/australia-news/2023/nov/09/small-modular-nuclear-reactor-that-was-hailed-by-coalition-as-future-cancelled-due-to-rising-costs |access-date=November 9, 2023 |newspaper=The Guardian}}</ref> $4.2 billion of the cost would be covered by the DOE and IRA support, leaving $5.1 billion of acquisition and construction costs to be covered by UAMPS members.<ref name="cfpp-20230102">{{cite web |last=Webb |first=LaVarr |date=January 2, 2023 |title=Meeting Talking Points |url=https://cdnsm5-hosted.civiclive.com/UserFiles/Servers/Server_6435726/File/Government/Departments/Public%20Utilities/CFPP/Talking%20Points%20_%20Class%203%20_%2020230102%20_%20Final.pdf |access-date=November 9, 2023 |website=Carbon Free Power Project}}</ref>

In November 2023, UAMPS announced it was unlikely that the project would have enough subscription to continue due to cost increases, and UAMPS and NuScale jointly decided to cancel the project.<ref name="wnn-20231109">{{cite news |date=November 9, 2023 |title=Idaho SMR project terminated |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/Idaho-SMR-project-terminated |access-date=November 9, 2023 |website=World Nuclear News}}</ref><ref name="eenews-20231109" /> ''POWER magazine'' reported that the project had received $232 million of DOE financial support by the time it was cancelled.<ref name="power-20231108">{{cite news |last=Larson |first=Aaron |date=November 8, 2023 |title=UAMPS and NuScale Power Terminate SMR Nuclear Project |url=https://www.powermag.com/uamps-and-nuscale-power-terminate-smr-nuclear-project/ |access-date=November 14, 2023 |work=POWER magazine}}</ref>

Following the cancellation, NuScale laid off 154 of its staff (28%) as part of "taking steps to transition from R&D to commercialization".<ref name="nei-20240109">{{cite news |date=January 9, 2024 |title=NuScale lays off almost a third of its workforce |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/nuscale-lays-off-almost-half-its-workforce-11422870/?cf-view |access-date=August 15, 2024 |publisher=Nuclear Engineering International}}</ref>

=== Doicești, Romania ===
In November 2021, NuScale announced its intent to build with [[Nuclearelectrica]] its first reactors in Romania by 2028.<ref>{{Cite web |title=NuScale SMR planned for Romania : New Nuclear – World Nuclear News<!-- Bot generated title --> |url=https://world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/NuScale-SMR-planned-for-Romania |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211106190149/https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/NuScale-SMR-planned-for-Romania |archive-date=November 6, 2021 |access-date=November 6, 2021}}</ref>

On December 28, 2022, Romanian company RoPower Nuclear contracted for Front-End Engineering and Design. The location was expected to be at [[Doicești Power Station]], a former [[thermal power station]]. RoPower is a joint venture between [[Nuclearelectrica]] and Nove Power & Gas.<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 4, 2023 |title=NuScale Power şi RoPower Nuclear au semnat un contract pentru amplasarea primei centrale SMR în România |url=https://adevarul.ro/economie/nuscale-power-si-ropower-nuclear-au-semnat-un-2232244.html |language=ro}}</ref>

On July 25, 2024, RoPower Nuclear and Fluor Corporation signed the second stage Front-End Engineering and Design (FEED 2) contract, for the planned SMR project in Romania which will provide updated cost estimate and other analysis for a final investment decision.<ref>{{Cite web |title=RoPower and Fluor sign FEED 2 contract for SMR project : New Nuclear – World Nuclear News |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/RoPower-and-Fluor-Corporation-sign-FEED-2-contract |access-date=August 14, 2024 |website=www.world-nuclear-news.org}}</ref> The [[Export–Import Bank of the United States]] approved a $98 million loan to RoPower Nuclear to support this design study, which would support 400 US jobs.<ref name="wnn-20241002">{{cite news |date=October 2, 2024 |title=US Exim Bank approves loan for Romanian SMR project |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/articles/us-exim-bank-approves-loan-for-romanian-smr-project |access-date=October 9, 2024 |website=World Nuclear News}}</ref>

In February 2026, Nuclearelectrica made a decision in principle to invest in a 6-module NuScale SMR, subject to devising a funding plan. The Romanian Prime Minister [[Ilie Bolojan]] estimated the cost at $6-$7 billion and said "the complexity of such projects and the technology being in early days, I estimate we will not see the investment immediately."<ref name="reuters-20260213">{{cite news |last=Ilie |first=Luiza |date=February 13, 2026 |title=Planned SMR nuclear power plant to cost -7 billion, Romanian PM says |url=https://www.reuters.com/business/energy/planned-smr-nuclear-power-plant-cost-6-7-billion-romanian-pm-says-2026-02-13/ |url-access=limited |access-date=February 15, 2026 |publisher=Reuters}}</ref> RoPower Nuclear will only pay for the first reactor module with NuScale responsible for the other five until the first module demonstrates full operation, which is planned for July 2033.<ref name="bgen-20260213">{{cite news |date=February 13, 2026 |title=Romania to build one small reactor to test before proceeding with six-unit SMR project |url=https://balkangreenenergynews.com/romania-to-build-one-small-reactor-to-test-before-proceeding-with-six-unit-smr-project/ |access-date=February 16, 2026 |website=Balkan Green Energy News}}</ref>

=== Other plans ===
In March 2012, NuScale signed an agreement with DOE that allowed NuScale and two partners to build and operate a NuScale-based nuclear power plant at a [[Savannah River site]] in [[South Carolina]].<ref name="powerone">{{cite news |last=Patel |first=Sonal |date=July 1, 2012 |title=Small Modular Reactors Vie for DOE Funding |url=http://www.powermag.com/small-modular-reactors-vie-for-doe-funding/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718083459/http://www.powermag.com/small-modular-reactors-vie-for-doe-funding/ |archive-date=July 18, 2014 |access-date=January 17, 2015}}</ref> The following month, [[Energy Northwest]] said it had no immediate plans to construct a nuclear power plant, but had evaluated all the available SMR technologies and identified NuScale as the best available option.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beattie |first=Jeff |date=June 18, 2012 |title=Washington Governor Nudging DOE For Small Nuke At Hanford |url=http://www.theenergydaily.com/nuclear/Washington-Governor-Nudging-DOE-For-Small-Nuke-At-Hanford_8070.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210201021624/https://www.theenergydaily.com/Login?returnUrl=%2Fted%2Fdocument%2F8070 |archive-date=February 1, 2021 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=The Energy Daily}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Beattie |first=Jeff |date=July 26, 2012 |title=FirstEnergy Eyeing Possible B&W Small Reactor Project |url=http://www.theenergydaily.com/publications/ed/2012-07-26/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304135525/http://www.theenergydaily.com/publications/ed/2012-07-26/ |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=The Energy Daily}}</ref>

In July 2013, NuScale announced an effort to demonstrate NuScale reactors in the western United States, called Program WIN (Western Initiative for Nuclear),<ref name="fifteen" /> with plans to build the first NuScale-based power plant there by 2024.<ref name="profile" />

In January 2018, the NRC agreed that the passive safety features allow NuScale's SMR design to operate safely without back-up power.<ref>{{Cite web |title=NRC agrees NuScale SMR needs no back-up power |url=http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-NRC-agrees-NuScale-SMR-needs-no-back-up-power-1001184.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126185512/http://www.world-nuclear-news.org/RS-NRC-agrees-NuScale-SMR-needs-no-back-up-power-1001184.html |archive-date=January 26, 2018 |access-date=January 26, 2018 |publisher=World Nuclear News}}</ref>

In August 2020, the NRC issued a final safety evaluation report, certifying the design as having met safety requirements.<ref name=":0" /><ref>{{cite web |last=Johnson |first=Scott K. |date=September 1, 2020 |title=NuScale's small nuclear reactor is first to get US safety approval |url=https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/09/first-modular-nuclear-reactor-design-certified-in-the-us/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200901233752/https://arstechnica.com/science/2020/09/first-modular-nuclear-reactor-design-certified-in-the-us/ |archive-date=September 1, 2020 |access-date=September 2, 2020 |work=[[Ars Technica]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |author=Patel, Sona |date=November 11, 2020 |title=NuScale Boosts SMR Module Capacity; UAMPS Mulls Downsizing Nuclear Project |url=https://www.powermag.com/nuscale-boosts-smr-module-capacity-uamps-mulls-downsizing-nuclear-project/ |website=Power Magazine}}</ref>

In February 2022, NuScale and mining conglomerate [[KGHM Polska Miedź|KGHM]] announced a contract to construct an SMR in Poland by 2029.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Patel |first=Sonal |date=February 15, 2022 |title=Poland Secures NuScale SMR as Urgency for Nuclear Energy Ramps Up Across Central, Eastern Europe |url=https://www.powermag.com/poland-secures-nuscale-smr-as-urgency-for-nuclear-energy-ramps-up-across-central-eastern-europe/ |access-date=May 11, 2022 |website=POWER Magazine |language=en-US}}</ref> In April 2023, an application for a decision-in-principle to permit the project was submitted to the Polish government.<ref name="wnn-20230418">{{cite news |date=April 18, 2023 |title=KGHM seeks approval for SMR project |url=https://www.world-nuclear-news.org/Articles/KGHM-seeks-approval-for-SMR-project |access-date=August 14, 2024 |website=World Nuclear News}}</ref>

In January 2023, the NRC certified NuScale's 50 MWe design, known as the VOYGR, for use in the US.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web |last=McDermott |first=Jennifer |date=January 20, 2023 |title=1st small modular nuclear reactor certified for use in US |url=https://apnews.com/article/us-nuclear-regulatory-commission-oregon-climate-and-environment-business-design-e5c54435f973ca32759afe5904bf96ac |access-date=January 21, 2023 |website=AP NEWS |language=en}}</ref> However this was for an earlier version of the design to the current 77 MWe design. The module and plant designs were resubmitted to the NRC in January 2023 for NuScale Power's four and six-reactor configurations, known as VOYGR-4 (US300) and VOYGR-6 (US460).<ref name="mittr-20230208">{{cite news |last=Crownhart |first=Casey |date=February 8, 2023 |title=We were promised smaller nuclear reactors. Where are they? |url=https://www.technologyreview.com/2023/02/08/1067992/smaller-nuclear-reactors/ |access-date=March 29, 2023 |website=MIT Technology Review}}</ref> In its acceptance review of the application, the NRC identified a number of sufficiency issues in the application, and requested supplemental information be supplied before NRC staff could accept the application for docketing and detailed technical review.<ref name="nrc-20230317">{{cite web |last=Tesfaye |first=Getachew |date=March 17, 2023 |title=Acceptance Review of the Nuscale US460 Standard Design Approval Application (Docket Nos. 05200050 and 99902078) |url=https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ML2305/ML23058A160.pdf |access-date=August 20, 2024 |publisher=Nuclear Regulatory Commission}}</ref> The supplemental information  was supplied in July 2023, and the NRC estimated the evaluation would be complete in July 2025.<ref name="nrc-20230731">{{cite web |last=Tesfaye |first=Getachew |date=July 31, 2023 |title=Acceptance Review of the Nuscale US460 Standard Design Approval Application (Docket Nos. 05200050 and 99902078) |url=https://www.nrc.gov/docs/ml2319/ml23198A163.pdf |access-date=August 20, 2024 |publisher=Nuclear Regulatory Commission}}</ref> In May 2025, NuScale successfully obtained NRC-US licensing for their 77 MWe module and the two new plant configurations.<ref>{{cite web |title=NRC Approves NuScale Power's Uprated Small Modular Reactor Design |url=https://www.energy.gov/ne/articles/nrc-approves-nuscale-powers-uprated-small-modular-reactor-design |access-date=June 7, 2025 |website=energy.gov |publisher=DOE}}</ref>

On August 29, 2024, Nuclear Power Ghana and Regnum Technology Group signed an agreement to build a 12-module nuclear power plant in Ghana during the US-Africa Nuclear Energy Summit in Nairobi, Kenya.<ref>{{Cite web |last=Belgium |first=Central Office, NucNet a s b l, Brussels |date=August 5, 2024 |title=Ghana / African Nation Signs Agreement For NuScale 12-Module Nuclear Power Plant |url=https://www.nucnet.org/news/african-nation-signs-agreement-for-nuscale-12-module-nuclear-power-plant-8-5-2024 |access-date=March 31, 2025 |website=The Independent Global Nuclear News Agency}}</ref> In January 2025, an SMR simulator training centre was opened in Ghana, to train and educate the next generation in operating future civil nuclear reactors.<ref>{{Cite web |date=January 27, 2025 |title=Ghana launches NuScale SMR simulator training centre |url=https://www.neimagazine.com/news/ghana-launches-first-nuscale-smr-simulator-training-centre/ |access-date=March 31, 2025 |website=Nuclear Engineering International |language=en-US}}</ref>

In 2023, NuScale submitted a new design for NRC approval to license its VOYGR-12. As of 2025, the 12-module, 924 MWe reactor design remains under NRC review.<ref name=":4" />

In June 2025, NuScale announced new research findings showing how their plants can be used in clean water, [[reverse osmosis]] and hydrogen generation applications. Simulations showed a single NuScale Power Module could yield approximately 150 million gallons of clean water per day without generating carbon dioxide. 12 NPMs would be able to provide desalinated water for a city of 2.3 million residents and 200 metric tons of hydrogen per day or a surplus of power to provide 400,000 homes with electricity.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Patel |first1=Sonal |title=NuScale Advances SMR-Powered Desalination and Hydrogen Production with Integrated Brine Reuse Strategy |url=https://www.powermag.com/nuscale-advances-smr-powered-desalination-and-hydrogen-production-with-integrated-brine-reuse-strategy/ |access-date=July 24, 2025 |website=powermag.com |publisher=Power}}</ref>

==Reactors==
[[File:Diagram of a NuScale reactor.png|thumb|upright|alt=A diagram of a NuScale SMR module.|A diagram of a NuScale SMR module.]]
NuScale reactors take 1% of the space of a conventional reactor and generate 77 [[MWe]].<ref name="nuscale-2021" /><ref>{{Cite web |last1=Cho |first1=Adrian |date=February 21, 2019 |title=Smaller, safer, cheaper: One company aims to reinvent the nuclear reactor and save a warming planet |url=https://www.science.org/content/article/smaller-safer-cheaper-one-company-aims-reinvent-nuclear-reactor-and-save-warming-planet |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200131154511/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2019/02/smaller-safer-cheaper-one-company-aims-reinvent-nuclear-reactor-and-save-warming-planet |archive-date=January 31, 2020 |access-date=January 31, 2020 |website=Science {{!}} AAAS |language=en}}</ref><ref name=science-20231110 /> The design uses light water for cooling and power generation as in conventional nuclear plants. Water is heated by the nuclear core, located at the base of the module. Heated water flows up the riser, then down over [[Steam generator (nuclear power)|steam generators]]. As heat is transferred, the water cools and becomes denser, sinking to the bottom of the module, and the cycle is repeated. The heat creates steam that drives a small dedicated [[turbine generator]] producing electricity.<ref name="profile" /><ref name="seventeen" /><ref name=nrc-20221231 />

The first NuScale Power Module design is {{convert|9|ft|m}} in diameter and {{convert|65|ft|m}} tall, weighing {{convert|650|ST|MT|abbr=off}}.<ref name="seventeen" /> The module is pre-fabricated, delivered by [[rail transport|rail]], [[barge]] or truck<ref>{{cite news |last=Barnard |first=Jeff |date=December 13, 2013 |title=Department Of Energy Awards Grant to NuScale to Design Small Modular Nuclear Power Plants |url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/13/department-of-energy-nuscale-grant_n_4438796.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160309063803/http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2013/12/13/department-of-energy-nuscale-grant_n_4438796.html |archive-date=March 9, 2016 |access-date=March 2, 2015 |publisher=Associated Press}}</ref> and assembled on-site.<ref name="eleven" /><ref name="popular">{{cite news |last=Hise |first=Phaedra |date=December 18, 2009 |title=Mini Reactors Show Promise for Clean Nuclear Power's Future |url=https://www.popularmechanics.com/science/energy/a3415/4273386/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160427041151/http://www.popularmechanics.com/science/energy/a3415/4273386/ |archive-date=April 27, 2016 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=Popular Mechanics}}</ref><ref name="four">{{cite news |date=January 1, 2009 |title=The Race to Commercialize Mini-Nuclear Reactors |url=http://www.powermag.com/the-race-to-commercialize-mininuclear-reactors/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718102721/http://www.powermag.com/the-race-to-commercialize-mininuclear-reactors/ |archive-date=July 18, 2014 |access-date=January 14, 2015 |newspaper=Power Magazine}}</ref><ref name="alpha">{{cite news |last=Blumenthal |first=Les |date=June 14, 2009 |title=Northwest Utilities Turn to Nuclear, 25 years After Industry Collapsed |url=http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2009/06/14/69983/northwest-utilities-turn-to-nuclear.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130508210020/http://www.mcclatchydc.com/2009/06/14/69983/northwest-utilities-turn-to-nuclear.html |archive-date=May 8, 2013 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=Tribune News Service}}</ref> The latest NRC approved power module delivers 77  MWe (gross), or about 73.5 MWe (net),<ref name="nuscale-2021">{{cite web |year=2021 |title=NuScale SMR Technology: An Ideal Solution for Repurposing U.S. Coal Plant Infrastructure and Revitalizing Communities NuScale |url=https://mc-67443a0a-0a3b-4888-8568-874354-cdn-endpoint.azureedge.net/-/media/Nuscale/Files/Technology/Technical-Publications/nuscale-smr-technology-an-ideal-solution.ashx?rev=d48edd73fb5f464f8bdb593a76a4aa38&hash=23600A270CB394AC79C1F7B662648859 |access-date=June 30, 2022 |publisher=NuScale}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Cunningham |first=Nick |date=March 24, 2015 |title=A Look At The Future Of Nuclear Power |url=http://oilprice.com/Alternative-Energy/Nuclear-Power/A-Look-At-The-Future-Of-Nuclear-Power.html |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150328211343/http://oilprice.com/Alternative-Energy/Nuclear-Power/A-Look-At-The-Future-Of-Nuclear-Power.html |archive-date=March 28, 2015 |access-date=April 9, 2015 |publisher=OilPrice}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date=June 6, 2018 |title=NuScale Boosts SMR Capacity, Making it Cost Competitive with Other Technologies |url=http://www.powermag.com/nuscale-boosts-smr-capacity-making-it-cost-competitive-with-other-technologies/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180610023455/http://www.powermag.com/nuscale-boosts-smr-capacity-making-it-cost-competitive-with-other-technologies/ |archive-date=June 10, 2018 |access-date=June 6, 2018 |newspaper=Power Magazine |quote=Optimization... will increase NuScale Power's small modular reactor (SMR) capacity by 20%... [This] would boost the power capacity of a 12-module SMR plant currently planned by Utah Associated Municipal Power Systems (UAMPS) from 600 MWe to 720 MWe."}}</ref>{{efn|Previously 45, 50, then 60 MWe}} and require refueling with standard 4.95 percent low-enriched [[uranium-235]] fuel every two years.<ref name="seventeen" />

NuScale's design does not rely on powered water pumps or circulatory equipment.<ref name="three">{{cite news |last=Durlin |first=Marty |date=March 30, 2009 |title=Mix-and-Match Nuclear Reactors |url=https://www.hcn.org/issues/41.5/innovate-part-iii |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150912202931/http://www.hcn.org/issues/41.5/innovate-part-iii |archive-date=September 12, 2015 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=High Country News}}</ref><ref name="profile" /> NuScale Power Modules are designed to shut down and cool indefinitely during most accidents.<ref name="profile" />{{efn|Most sources say indefinitely, but NBC News reported 30 days.<ref>{{cite news |date=October 10, 2011 |title=Will Next-Gen Nuclear Power be Safe Enough? |url=http://www.nbcnews.com/video/nbcnews.com/44793381 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304093026/http://www.nbcnews.com/video/nbcnews.com/44793381 |archive-date=March 4, 2016 |access-date=January 15, 2015 |publisher=NBC News}}</ref>}} The devices are intended to be installed in a below-ground pool to absorb earthquake shocks, with a concrete lid over the pool.<ref>{{cite news |last=Maize |first=Kennedy |date=July 1, 2011 |title=Nuclear Power in the Shadow of Fukushima |url=http://www.powermag.com/nuclear-power-in-the-shadow-of-fukushima/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140718090930/http://www.powermag.com/nuclear-power-in-the-shadow-of-fukushima/ |archive-date=July 18, 2014 |access-date=April 27, 2015 |newspaper=Power Magazine}}</ref> In the event that power is lost for normal cooling systems, the water in the pool absorbs heat and boils.<ref name="profile" /> The pool stores enough water to safely cool the latest 77 MWe module core for at least 72 hours without needing manual replenishment.<ref name="nrc-20221231">{{cite web |date=May 29, 2025 |title=NRC Approves Standard Design for NuScale US460 Small Modular Reactor |url=https://www.nrc.gov/cdn/doc-collection-news/2025/25-033.pdf |access-date=May 29, 2025 |website=NuScale Power |pages=1 |via=NRC}}</ref>

In normal operating conditions, the module's containment-vessel-pressure remains near vacuum, which eliminates convection and provides simpler heat transfer conditions. The effect also reduces component corrosion and improves instrumentation reliability.<ref name="profile" />

The reactor modules are installed in the reactor pool in individual bays separated by concrete walls. During refueling, the entire reactor is moved underwater through a transfer channel to a connected pool, which contains the refueling equipment. There is also an extra reactor bay for maintenance or possible storage of a spare module. At a 12-reactor plant, the bays are arranged in two rows of six reactors with the transfer channel centrally located between rows.<ref name="profile" />

===Comparisons===
[[File:NuScale-Upper-One-Third-Mockup.jpg|thumb|upright|Full-scale [[mockup]] of the upper one-third of the NuScale Power Module]]
NuScale is expected to be the first US SMR to market because it is similar to the systems used in conventional power plants.<ref name="discover">{{cite news |last=Freedman |first=David |date=June 2010 |title=The Big Potential of Micro Nukes |url=https://www.discovermagazine.com/environment/the-big-potential-of-micro-nukes |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191216130215/https://www.discovermagazine.com/environment/the-big-potential-of-micro-nukes |archive-date=December 16, 2019 |access-date=January 18, 2015 |publisher=Discover}}</ref> The company estimates a twelve-unit NuScale plant would cost $4,200 (an earlier estimate was $5,000) per kilowatt. In comparison, the [[Energy Information Administration]] in 2013 estimated overnight costs to be $4,700 per kilowatt for conventional nuclear power, $4,600 for a [[carbon sequestration]] coal plant and $931 at a gas-fired plant or in excess of $1,800 for a gas-fired plant with carbon sequestration (all 2011 dollars).<ref name="profile" /> David Mohre, executive director of [[NRECA]]'s Energy and Power Division, said SMRs like NuScale's are ideal for rural towns that need small power plants.<ref name="thirteen" />

NuScale power plants are expected to take less time, materials and space to construct than other power sources and can be expanded incrementally to meet growing power needs.<ref name="two" /><ref name="four" /><ref name="six">{{cite news |last=Barbe |first=Wayne |date=July 13, 2010 |title=NuScale Sees Large Upside in Small Nuclear Units |publisher=SNL Generation Markets Week}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Fairfield |first=Hannah |date=December 1, 2009 |title=New Scale for Nuclear Power |url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9405E6D7163BF932A35751C1A96F9C8B63 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150619175353/http://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9405E6D7163BF932A35751C1A96F9C8B63 |archive-date=June 19, 2015 |access-date=April 11, 2015 |newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> With the steam generators internal to the movable steel reactor assembly, the SMR does not have a large concrete [[secondary containment building]] as used in large PWRs. There is a single control room for up to 12 reactors.<ref name="eenews-20231110">{{cite news |last1=Bright |first1=Zach |last2=Dabbs |first2=Brian |date=November 10, 2023 |title=Is advanced nuclear in trouble? What's next after NuScale cancellation. |url=https://www.eenews.net/articles/is-advanced-nuclear-in-trouble-whats-next-after-nuscale-cancellation/ |access-date=November 28, 2023 |website=E&E News |publisher=POLITICO}}</ref> One disadvantage of the design is that the reactors lie in a large pool of water, for emergency cooling, and this pool requires much more reinforced concrete per MWe produced than a conventional nuclear reactor building, adding considerably to cost.<ref name="science-20231110">{{cite news |last=Cho |first=Adrian |date=November 10, 2023 |title=Deal to build pint-size nuclear reactors canceled |url=https://www.science.org/content/article/deal-build-pint-size-nuclear-reactors-canceled |access-date=November 11, 2023 |magazine=Science}}</ref>

''[[New Scientist]]'' reported peer‑reviewed analysis from [[Stanford University]] that assessed nuclear waste production from SMR reactors and concluded that "SMR performed worse on nearly all of our metrics compared to standard commercial reactors".<ref name="vaughan-2022">{{cite journal |last1=Vaughan |first1=Adam |date=May 30, 2022 |title=Mini nuclear power stations may produce more waste than large ones |url=https://www.newscientist.com/article/2322252-mini-nuclear-power-stations-may-produce-more-waste-than-large-ones/ |journal=New Scientist |issn=0262-4079 |access-date=May 31, 2022}}  {{closed access}}</ref><ref name="krall-etal-2022">{{cite journal |last1=Krall |first1=Lindsay M |last2=Macfarlane |first2=Allison M |last3=Ewing |first3=Rodney C |date=June 7, 2022 |title=Nuclear waste from small modular reactors |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=119 |issue=23 |pages=–2111833119 |bibcode=2022PNAS..11911833K |doi=10.1073/pnas.2111833119 |issn=0027-8424 |pmc=9191363 |pmid=35639689 |s2cid=249237378 |doi-access=free}}  {{open access}}</ref> The results of the study were rejected by NuScale as based on outdated information.<ref name="vaughan-2022" />

Potential SMR competitors include [[Babcock & Wilcox]], [[GE Vernova Hitachi Nuclear Energy]], [[Gen4 Energy]], [[Holtec International]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=A Generation Ahead By Design |url=https://holtecinternational.com/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210112142329/https://holtecinternational.com/ |archive-date=January 12, 2021 |access-date=January 11, 2021 |website=Holtec International |language=en-US}}</ref> [[Intellectual Ventures]], [[OPEN100]],<ref>{{cite news |last=Proctor |first=Darrell |date=February 25, 2020 |title=Tech Guru's Plan—Fight Climate Change with Nuclear Power |url=https://www.powermag.com/tech-gurus-plan-fight-climate-change-with-nuclear-power/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211020031103/https://www.powermag.com/tech-gurus-plan-fight-climate-change-with-nuclear-power/ |archive-date=October 20, 2021 |access-date=October 18, 2021 |work=Power Magazine}}</ref> [[Westinghouse Electric Company]], [[Terrestrial Energy]], and [[X-energy]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Proctor |first=Darrell |date=January 2, 2020 |title=U.S. Company Has Deal with Jordan for Nuclear Technology |url=https://www.powermag.com/u-s-company-has-deal-with-jordan-for-nuclear-technology/ |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20211020011145/https://www.powermag.com/u-s-company-has-deal-with-jordan-for-nuclear-technology/ |archive-date=October 20, 2021 |access-date=October 18, 2021 |work=Power Magazine}}</ref>

=== Safety concerns ===
In March 2020, a panel of independent experts from the NRC's Advisory Committee on Reactor Safeguards (ACRS) claimed to find reactor design flaws.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web |last=Cho |date=August 18, 2020 |title=Smaller, cheaper reactor aims to revive nuclear industry, but design problems raise safety concerns |url=https://www.science.org/content/article/smaller-cheaper-reactor-aims-revive-nuclear-industry-design-problems-raise-safety |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210227095017/https://www.sciencemag.org/news/2020/08/smaller-cheaper-reactor-aims-revive-nuclear-industry-design-problems-raise-safety |archive-date=February 27, 2021 |access-date=February 25, 2021 |website=Science {{!}} AAAS |language=en}}</ref> The main issue was that in the event of an emergency shutdown condensed steam returning to the reactor vessel would be low in [[boron]] and might not absorb enough [[neutrons]]. NuScale modified its design to ensure that more boron would spread to the returning water. ACRS was concerned that operators could accidentally add deboronated water to the core. The panel found other problems: the steam generator could be prone to damaging vibrations. However, on July 29 ACRS recommended that the safety evaluation report be issued and the reactor be certified.<ref name=":1" />

==Operations==
NuScale has offices in [[Tigard, Oregon]]; [[Corvallis, Oregon]]; [[Charlotte, North Carolina]]; and [[Rockville, Maryland]].<ref name="primaryone">{{citation |title=locations |url=http://www.nuscalepower.com/locations.aspx |access-date=January 15, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141228040134/http://www.nuscalepower.com/locations.aspx |archive-date=December 28, 2014 |url-status=live |publisher=NuScale}}</ref> Its headquarters are in Tigard, while its factory is in Corvallis.<ref>{{cite news |last=Giegerich |first=Andy |date=July 28, 2014 |title=NuScale set to add scores of Oregon jobs |url=http://www.bizjournals.com/portland/blog/2014/07/nuscale-set-to-add-scores-of-oregon-jobs.html |access-date=January 15, 2015 |newspaper=Portland Business Journal}}</ref> It maintains a test facility at [[Oregon State University]]<ref name="three" /> and in Italy.<ref name="profile" />

The company is publicly traded as SMR on the [[New York Stock Exchange]].<ref name=":3" />

